The increase of the feed speed increases surface topography parameters such as average height of the selected area (
Sa
) , root-mean-square height of the selected area (
Sq
) , or maximum valley depth of the selected area (
Sv
) .

The roughness parameters were found to be similar for both strategies ( perpendicular and inclined by 1 °) ; however , a greater increase of roughness parameters was observed while using higher feed speeds for samples machined with the tool inclined by 1 °. The average height of the selected area (
Sa
) showed higher values for samples machined with the tool inclined by 1 °.

This parameter was not adequate , considering that maximum valley depth of the selected area (
Sv
) was higher for samples machined by a tool positioned perpendicularly to the machined surface .
